<paragraph blockId="38.[192,1440,1091,1211]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,751,1091,1115]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Identification, taxonomy, and variation.</emphasis>
This subspecies bears cream to whitish colored ventral hindwing spots and a brick red disc. The marginal band along the disc is pinkish rather than buff. Adult wingspan ranges from 
<quantity box="[478,607,1155,1179]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="4.5" pageId="38" pageNumber="37" unit="mm" value="50.0" valueMax="55.0" valueMin="45.0">45-55 mm</quantity>
. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Gunder" baseAuthorityYear="1931" box="[619,926,1155,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="hesperis" subSpecies="dodgei">
<emphasis box="[619,926,1155,1179]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Speyeria hesperis dodgei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1067,1202,1155,1179]" class="Insecta" family="Nymphalidae" genus="Speyeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="38" pageNumber="37" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hydaspe">
<emphasis box="[1067,1202,1155,1179]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">S. hydaspe</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms where these species overlap.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[192,1186,1251,1276]" box="[192,1186,1251,1276]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,287,1251,1275]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Range.</emphasis>
Cascade ranges of 
<collectingRegion box="[514,603,1251,1275]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Oregon</collectingRegion>
and southern 
<collectingRegion box="[776,927,1251,1275]" country="United States of America" name="Washington" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Washington</collectingRegion>
, eastward into 
<collectingRegion box="[1108,1182,1251,1275]" country="United States of America" name="Idaho" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Idaho</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[192,1440,1315,1371]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,360,1315,1339]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37">Life history.</emphasis>
This subspecies is largely confined fir and pine forests and may be seen in canyons, along creeks, and in small clearings and meadows. 
<bibRefCitation author="Dornfeld, E. J." box="[734,924,1347,1371]" pageId="38" pageNumber="37" refId="ref35666" refString="Dornfeld, E. J. 1980. The butterflies of Oregon. Timber Press; Forest Grove, Oregon. 276 p." type="book" year="1980">Dornfeld (1980)</bibRefCitation>
briefly described the larva.
</paragraph>
